ST 558 Project 1

Bennett McAuley

Overview

The purpose of this project was to write functions to manipulate and process data that come in various forms. The data consisted of .csv files with information from the Census Bureau.

The first section will go through the data processing ad hoc on the first portion of the bureau data. Following, the method is repeated via function calls–that will be defined–on the second portion of the data set. Finally, we will define a function for plotting to apply on data sets that were not used during processing to ensure the logic generalizes.

Data Processing

First, we need the data! The readr library is used to read in one section of the data.

library(readr)
sheet1 <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")
## Rows: 3198 Columns: 42
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (22): Area_name, STCOU, EDU010187N1, EDU010187N2, EDU010188N1, EDU010188...
## dbl (20): EDU010187F, EDU010187D, EDU010188F, EDU010188D, EDU010189F, EDU010...
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Of the columns, we only need to select Area_name (renamed to area_name), STCOU, and the ones that end in “D”:

sheet1 <- plyr::rename(sheet1, c("Area_name" = "area_name"))
 
sheet1 %>%
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))

For whatever reason, renaming the column did not work with the chaining method, even with explicitly calling out the library. So I used the workaround shown above. It works for what we needed, so we will move on.

Next, we convert the data into long format where each row has only one enrollment value per area_name. To accomplish this, we tell the pivot_longer function all of the columns that end in “D” should be pivoted. Those are named survey with the values named enrollment.

sheet1 %>%
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ends_with("D")), names_to = "survey", values_to = "enrollment")

Now, we parse out the years of the surveys and the first seven characters–three alphabetical and four digits–to create two new variables. Each are separated using an index (here it’s 7 since that’s where we want to split), so the year is retained in the latter column. Then the mutate function, with help from the substr and as.Date functions, captures the last two year digits, converts into a date to be recognized and converted correctly, formatted to only have the year shown, and finally converted to a numeric variable. Complicated, but after much trial and error, it proved to be a sustainable solution!

sheet1 %>%
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ends_with("D")), names_to = "survey", values_to = "enrollment") %>%
  separate(survey, into = c("measurement", "year"), sep = 7, convert = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(format(as.Date(substr(year, 1, 2), "%y"), format = "%Y")))

From here, we create two data sets for county level data and state level data. First, the manipulations done on the data thus far have been saved to a new object clean_sheet. The county data is generated using grepl to find and subset to rows that contain the format “County Name, DD” for area_name. The state data is generated using the negation of that logic.

To complete this step, we add a county class to the county_data tibble and do the same for the state_data tibble with a state class.

clean_sheet <- sheet1 %>%
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ends_with("D")), names_to = "survey", values_to = "enrollment") %>%
  separate(survey, into = c("measurement", "year"), sep = 7, convert = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(format(as.Date(substr(year, 1, 2), "%y"), format = "%Y")))

county_data <- clean_sheet %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

state_data <- clean_sheet %>%
  filter(!grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

class(county_data) <- c("county", class(county_data))
class(state_data) <- c("state", class(state_data))

For the county_data tibble, we create a new variable for the state (appropriately named state) each of the county measurements correspond to using sub. Reason being, we don’t have to worry about using indices for the varying lengths of the counties, just needing to find the ,, and capturing what comes after that. Also a good excuse to practice more pattern matching functions.

county_data %>%
  mutate(state = sub('.*, ', '', area_name))

For the state_data tibble, we create a variable division that corresponds to the Census Bureau-designated divisions for the states, of which there are nine (Note: written out mostly for my own reference and to easily copy/paste to the code):

  1. New England (Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, Vermont)
  2. Mid-Atlantic (New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania)
  3. East North Central (Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, Wisconsin)
  4. West North Central (Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota)
  5. South Atlantic (Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Maryland, North Carolina, South Carolina, Virginia, District of Columbia, West Virginia)
  6. East South Central (Alabama, Kentucky, Mississippi, Tennessee)
  7. West South Central (Arkansas, Louisiana, Oklahoma, Texas)
  8. Mountain (Arizona, Colorado, Idaho, Montana, New Mexico, Nevada, Utah, Wyoming)
  9. Pacific (Alaska, California, Hawaii, Oregon, Washington)

The %in% operator makes this task simple, but unfortunately, no less tedious for writing out the conditions! Any non-state areas that don’t belong to a division (United States, mainly) are returned as ERROR.

state_data %>%
  mutate(division = case_when(area_name %in% c("CONNECTICUT", "MAINE", "MASSACHUSETTS", "NEW HAMPSHIRE", "RHODE ISLAND", "VERMONT") ~ "NEW ENGLAND",
                              area_name %in% c("NEW JERSEY", "NEW YORK", "PENNSYLVANIA") ~ "MID-ALTANTIC",
                              area_name %in% c("ILLINOIS", "INDIANA", "MICHIGAN", "OHIO", "WISCONSIN") ~ "EAST N. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("IOWA", "KANSAS", "MINNESOTA", "MISSOURI", "NEBRASKA", "NORTH DAKOTA", "SOUTH DAKOTA") ~ "WEST N. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("DELAWARE", "FLORIDA", "GEORGIA", "MARYLAND", "NORTH CAROLINA", "SOUTH CAROLINA", "VIRGINIA", "DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA", "WEST VIRGINIA") ~ "S. ATLANTIC",
                              area_name %in% c("ALABAMA", "KENTUCKY", "MISSISSIPPI", "TENNESSEE") ~ "EAST S. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("ARKANSAS", "LOUISIANA", "OKLAHOMA", "TEXAS") ~ "WEST S. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("ARIZONA", "COLORADO", "IDAHO", "MONTANA", "NEW MEXICO", "NEVADA", "UTAH", "WYOMING") ~ "MOUNTAIN",
                              area_name %in% c("ALASKA", "CALIFORNIA", "HAWAII", "OREGON", "WASHINGTON") ~ "PACIFIC",
                              TRUE ~ "ERROR")
)

Function Definitions

Now we will repeat the data processing on the second component of the data, but this time using functions! Each step or set of steps will have their own functions defined to accomplish the tasks, and a wrapper function to put it all together and execute with a single call!

The first function csv.input returns the data set that is read in. The link is the only variable for it to take.

csv.input <- function(link) {
  library(readr)
  return(read_csv(link))
}

The second function select.pivot, reflects steps 1 & 2. It returns a tibble with the columns we’re interested in from the data set in long format. This function takes two variables:

  • tibble: The name of the object returned from csv.input
  • valname: The name of the values for the generated column after pivoting (default is enrollment)
select.pivot <- function(tibble, valname = "enrollment") {
  tibble <- plyr::rename(tibble, c("Area_name" = "area_name"))

  tibble %>%
    select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) %>%
    pivot_longer(cols = c(ends_with("D")), names_to = "survey", values_to = valname)
}

The third function survey.split reflects step 3. It takes the returned object from select.pivot and creates the new variables that reflect the survey measurement code and year from splitting survey.

survey.split <- function(tibble) {
  tibble %>%
    separate(survey, into = c("measurement", "year"), sep = 7, convert = TRUE) %>%
    mutate(year = as.numeric(format(as.Date(substr(year, 1, 2), "%y"), format = "%Y")))
}

The fourth function add.state reflects step 5. It takes a single variable county_lvl for the tibble with the county level data, and creates the variable for states from area_name.

add.state <- function(county_lvl) {
  county_lvl %>%
  mutate(state = sub('.*, ', '', area_name))
}

The fifth function add.division reflects step 6. It takes the variable state_lvl for the tibble with the state level data, and creates the variable for divisions from area_name.

add.division <- function(state_lvl) {
  state_lvl %>%
  mutate(division = case_when(area_name %in% c("CONNECTICUT", "MAINE", "MASSACHUSETTS", "NEW HAMPSHIRE", "RHODE ISLAND", "VERMONT") ~ "NEW ENGLAND",
                              area_name %in% c("NEW JERSEY", "NEW YORK", "PENNSYLVANIA") ~ "MID-ALTANTIC",
                              area_name %in% c("ILLINOIS", "INDIANA", "MICHIGAN", "OHIO", "WISCONSIN") ~ "EAST N. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("IOWA", "KANSAS", "MINNESOTA", "MISSOURI", "NEBRASKA", "NORTH DAKOTA", "SOUTH DAKOTA") ~ "WEST N. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("DELAWARE", "FLORIDA", "GEORGIA", "MARYLAND", "NORTH CAROLINA", "SOUTH CAROLINA", "VIRGINIA", "DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA", "WEST VIRGINIA") ~ "S. ATLANTIC",
                              area_name %in% c("ALABAMA", "KENTUCKY", "MISSISSIPPI", "TENNESSEE") ~ "EAST S. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("ARKANSAS", "LOUISIANA", "OKLAHOMA", "TEXAS") ~ "WEST S. CENTRAL",
                              area_name %in% c("ARIZONA", "COLORADO", "IDAHO", "MONTANA", "NEW MEXICO", "NEVADA", "UTAH", "WYOMING") ~ "MOUNTAIN",
                              area_name %in% c("ALASKA", "CALIFORNIA", "HAWAII", "OREGON", "WASHINGTON") ~ "PACIFIC",
                              TRUE ~ "ERROR")
)
}

The sixth and final function before implementation of the wrapper, create.data, reflects step 4. It takes the returned object from survey.split and splits the data into county and state level sets. Then, it adds identically named classes to both. Finally, it calls add.state and add.division to complete the processing and returns the data sets in a list.

create.data <- function(tibble) {
county_lvl <- tibble %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

state_lvl <- tibble %>%
  filter(!grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

class(county_lvl) <- c("county", class(county_lvl))
class(state_lvl) <- c("state", class(state_lvl))


return(list(add.state(county_lvl), add.division(state_lvl)))
}

Now we will put all of the functions together into one wrapper function, called data.wrap. It takes the url and var (same function as valname) for its inputs, calls the functions defined, and returns the two tibbles.

data.wrap <- function(url, var) {
  t <- csv.input(url)
  u <- select.pivot(t, var)
  v <- survey.split(u)
  w <- create.data(v)
  
  return(w)
}

Success! Now we write a small function lvl.combine that takes the results of the calls above and combines the tibbles such that they are homogeneous (i.e. county level A with county level B).

lvl.combine <- function(tA, tB) {
  
  all_county <- dplyr::bind_rows(tA[[1]], tB[[1]])
  all_state <- dplyr::bind_rows(tA[[2]], tB[[2]])
  
  return(list(all_county, all_state))
}

Generic Functions for Summarizing

Our data sets have their own classes that we can used to write a custom plot function. First we will define a function for state, plot.state. It takes the combined data set and it plots the mean value of the enrollment across the years for each division, omitting observations that have ERROR.

plot.state <- function(df, var = "enrollment") {
  new_df <- df %>%
    group_by(division, year) %>%
    summarize(xbar = mean(get(var))) %>%
    filter(division != 'ERROR')
  
  ggplot(new_df, aes(x = year, y = xbar, color = division)) + geom_line()
}

Now we will define a plotting function for county, plot.county, that will provide more flexibility. It still returns a plot, but with some options for the variables:

  • st: The state of interest. The data is filtered is only include observations in the state specified
  • rank: Whether the highest (top) or lowest (bottom) ranked counties should be investigated
  • n: The number of top/bottom counties to include in the plot

The function calculates the mean of enrollment for each area_name and sorts these values from largest to smallest if rank is top and vice versa for bottom. Then it takes the n number of counties specified and filters the data down to those. This is the data used to plot, which is what is returned.

plot.county <- function(df, var = "enrollment", st = 'NC', rank = 'top', n = 5) {
  df_sort <- df %>%
    filter(state == st) %>%
    group_by(area_name) %>%
    summarize(mean = mean(get(var)))
  
  ifelse(rank == 'top', x <- df_sort %>% arrange(desc(mean)), x <- df_sort %>% arrange(mean))
    
  v <- c(x %>%
    select(area_name) %>%
    filter(between(row_number(), 1, n)))
  
  df_plot <- df %>%
    filter(area_name %in% v$area_name)
  
  ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = year, y = get(var), color = area_name)) + geom_line()
}
